Explanation
- The controller class has no class-level @RequestMapping, so the method-level paths are full paths as written.
- There are two handler methods annotated for the exact path "/printshops/requests/{id}":
  - changeStatusPrintShopRequests(...) is annotated with @RequestMapping(value = "/printshops/requests/{id}", method = RequestMethod.POST) — so POST is explicitly supported.
  - getPrintShopRequest(...) is annotated with @RequestMapping(value = "/printshops/requests/{id}", method = RequestMethod.GET) — so GET is explicitly supported.
- No handler in this class maps HEAD, OPTIONS, TRACE, PUT, DELETE, PATCH, or a wildcard/all-methods mapping for that path, so those methods are considered not acceptable based solely on the code. (Note: frameworks may implicitly handle some methods like HEAD, but the answer above follows only explicit mappings in the source code as requested.)
